e with people who agree with us, forming culturally cohesive social circles based upon similar viewpoints, and unconsciously referencing only those perspectives which reaffirm our deeply entrenched beliefs -- [[http://www.huffingtonpost.ca/adam-kingsmith/self-censorship-reading-online_b_2403378.html | as I've written before]], the Internet can in part be attributed to the increasing prevalence of this bias.%0a%3c %0a---%0a> '''1) [[http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Confirmation_bias | Confirmation bias]]''' -- We tend to agree with people who agree with us, forming culturally cohesive social circles based upon similar viewpoints, and unconsciously referencing only those perspectives which reaffirm our deeply entrenched beliefs -- [[http://www.huffingtonpost.ca/adam-kingsmith/self-censorship-reading-online_b_2403378.html | as I've written before]], the Internet can in part be attributed to the increasing prevalence of this bias.%0a> %0a29,30c269,270%0a%3c # [[http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/In-group_favoritism | Ingroup bias]]''' -- Similarly to confirmation bias, due to our species innate tribal desire to be socially accepted, we tend to favour the thoughts, ideals, and sentiments of those with whom we racially, culturally, and ethnocentrically identify with most.%0a%3c %0a---%0a> '''2) [[http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/In-group_favoritism | Ingroup bias]]''' -- Similarly to confirmation bias, due to our species innate tribal desire to be socially accepted, we tend to favour the thoughts, ideals, and sentiments of those with whom we racially, culturally, and ethnocentrically identify with most.%0a> %0a33,34c273,274%0a%3c # [[http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Status_quo_bias | Status-quo bias]]''' -- Due to our unproven assumption that fresh alternatives are inferior to our current state of affairs, we are apprehensive of change. Thus people's preferences tend to be motivated by a desire to keep things as familiar as possible.%0a%3c %0a---%0a> '''3) [[http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Status_quo_bias | Status-quo bias]]''' -- Due to our unproven assumption that fresh alternatives are inferior to our current state of affairs, we are apprehensive of change. Thus people's preferences tend to be motivated by a desire to keep things as familiar as possible.%0a> %0a37,38c277,278%0a%3c # [[http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Negativity_bias | Negativity bias]]''' -- People seem to give more weight to negative experiences -- not just because we're morbid, but because given the choice, our cognitive selective attention processes identify negative news as inherently important or profound.%0a%3c %0a---%0a> '''4) [[http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Negativity_bias | Negativity bias]]''' -- People seem to give more weight to negative experiences -- not just because we're morbid, but because given the choice, our cognitive selective attention processes identify negative news as inherently important or profound.%0a> %0a41,42c281,282%0a%3c # [[http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/False-consensus_effect | False-consensus bias]]''' -- As we are limited in understanding circumstances outside of our own consciousness, we tend to believe that most other people think just like we do -- although there may be no justification for such an assumption.%0a%3c %0a---%0a> '''5) [[http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/False-consensus_effect | False-consensus bias]]''' -- As we are limited in understanding circumstances outside of our own consciousness, we tend to believe that most other people think just like we do -- although there may be no justification for such an assumption.%0a> %0a45,46c285,286%0a%3c # [[http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tragedy_of_the_commons#The_commons_dilemma | Temporal bias]]''' -- A psychological tragedy of the commons, we have much difficulty imagining ourselves and our global commons in the future, and thus we struggle at altering our behaviours in order to safeguard said imagined future.%0a%3c %0a---%0a> '''6) [[http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tragedy_of_the_commons#The_commons_dilemma | Temporal bias]]''' -- A psychological tragedy of the commons, we have much difficulty imagining ourselves and our global commons in the future, and thus we struggle at altering our behaviours in order to safeguard said imagined future.%0a> %0a55,58c295,405%0a%3c >>%3c%3c%0a%3c %0a%3c ''Follow Adam Kingsmith on Twitter: [[http://www.twitter.com/akingsmith |  www.twitter.com/akingsmith ]]''%0a%3c %0a---%0a> &nbsp; \\%0a> %0a> ''' Follow Adam Kingsmith on Twitter: [[http://www.twitter.com/akingsmith |  www.twitter.com/akingsmith ]] '''%0a> %0a>  FOLLOW CANADA POLITICS [[javascript:void(0); | Like]]''''38k[[ | &nbsp;]] [[ |  Get Alerts]]%0a> %0a> * [[http://www.huffingtonpost.com/news/politics/ | Politics]]%0a> * [[http://www.huffingtonpost.com/news/emotional-intelligence/ | Emotional Intelligence]]%0a> * [[http://www.huffingtonpost.com/news/mental-health/ | Mental Health]]%0a> %0a> [[http://www.huffingtonpost.ca:80/# | &nbsp;]] ''Loading...''&nbsp;[[#comments]]&nbsp; [[http://www.huffingtonpost.ca:80/# | http://s.huffpost.com/images/comments/display_comments_title.gif]]%0a> %0a> * Comments%0a> * 0%0a> * Pending Comments%0a> * 0%0a> * [[http://www.huffingtonpost.com/p/frequently-asked-question.html#moderation | View FAQ]]%0a> %0a> [[#postComment]]http://s.huffpost.com/images/snn-logo-comments.png%0a> %0a> ! Previewing Your Comment.%0a> %0a>  This comment has not yet been posted  You have exceeded your word limit by &nbsp;&nbsp; words. Please click the "Edit" button and shorten your comment. \\%0a>  \\%0a> [[http://www.huffingtonpost.ca:80/# |  Post Comment ]] [[http://www.huffingtonpost.ca:80/# |   Edit   ]] [[http://www.huffingtonpost.ca:80/# |   Cancel   ]]      \\%0a>  \\%0a> You can post to us this information [[javascript:void(0); | Contact us]] [[javascript:void(0); | http://s.huffpost.com/images/close-gray.png]]Click here to leave a comment.%0a> %0a> HuffPost High School welcomes a lively, thoughtful debate in the comment section. Keep in mind that the artic